<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,583,752]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Originally described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[477,606,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Lasiochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[477,606,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Lasiochilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. According to the original description, this is also clearly a species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[151,234,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,234,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Dilasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the following characters: the wide and apically truncate male left paramere, dorsal surface smooth and widened forefemorae. Herring did not mention spines or teeth on tibiae, but then he did not refer to this character in any of six species he described in this paper.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
